-- 
Thailand Stocks: Home Product, LH Financial, Siam Industrial

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-05-10T09:57:30Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-10/advanced-info-home-product-lh-financial-thai-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  Thailand  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 4:30 p.m. close in Bangkok.  The SET Index rose 13.09, or 1.2 percent, to 1,085.56.  Bangkok Expressway Pcl (BECL)  , Thailand’s largest
private tollroad operator, climbed 1.1 percent to 18.10 baht,
the most since Dec. 30. Net income in the first quarter
increased 38 percent to 538.5 million baht ($17.8 million).  Ch. Karnchang Pcl (CK TB), the country’s second-biggest
publicly traded construction company, dropped 3 percent to 8
baht, the lowest close since March 18. Laos’s government will
ask Ch. Karnchang to pay for a review of a $3.8 billion
hydropower dam on the Mekong River after downstream countries
called for a delay to further study environmental concerns,
Daovong Phonekeo, deputy director general of Laos’s Department
of Electricity, said by phone today from Vientiane.  Home Product Center Pcl (HMPRO)  , the nation’s largest
retailer of home improvement materials, gained 3.6 percent to
8.55 baht, the most since April 12. Net income in the first
quarter rose 21 percent to 408 million baht.  LH Financial Group Pcl (LHBANK TB) jumped 28 percent to
1.79 baht in its trading debut. The company sold 1.44 billion
shares at 1.40 baht each in its initial public offering.  Siam Industrial Credit Pcl (SICCO)  , a financial company,
slid 9.3 percent to 4.28 baht, the steepest decline since Sept.
1.  Siam Commercial Bank Pcl (SCB)  , Siam Industrial’s biggest
shareholder with a 38.7 percent holding, said it didn’t receive
any bids for a stake it planned to sell. Siam Commercial climbed
2.2 percent to 117 baht.  Thai Film Industries Pcl (TFI)  , a maker of packaging
films, surged 19 percent to 2.72 baht, the highest close since
Jan. 13. The company had a profit of 67.5 million baht in the
three months ended March 31, compared with a net loss of 39.9
million baht in the same period a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anuchit Nguyen in Bangkok at 
 anguyen@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
